{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01Ed8m6vmSCQoLmdvaGuhA9f","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good -- I can see what's available. The local Maven cache has `hibernate-enhance-maven-plugin` versions:\n- 6.6.18.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.6.48.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.6.50.Final\n- 6.6.50.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.6.51.Final-redhat-00001\n\nAnd `hibernate-core` versions:\n- 6.2.13.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.2.18.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.6.3.Final\n- 6.6.37.Final\n- 6.6.48.Final-redhat-00001\n- 6.6.50.Final\n- 6.6.51.Final-redhat-00001\n- 7.1.11.Final\n\nNow I see the distinction between Experiments 3 and 5: Experiment 3 used the community 6.6.50.Final version with a minor version mismatch and no `@EnhancementInfo` annotation since that's not available in ORM 6.6.x, while Experiment 5 is the integration test that should verify how the WildFly JPA layer detects version mismatches. Since 6.6.x doesn't embed version metadata in the enhanced bytecode, the runtime can't catch the incompatibility at all. For Experiment 5, I should try a more substantial version gap using a productized variant like 6.6.48.Final-redhat-00001 to test whether the integration layer has its own version checking mechanism, or possibly deploy as an EAR to exercise the full integration stack. and detects the mismatch, or if it silently accepts the mismatched versions. I expect this to fail like Experiment 3 since the ORM version doesn't have built-in mismatch detection, but I'll run it to confirm. Now I'll write out the script.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5379,"cache_read_input_tokens":87620,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5379,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9bccde12-9349-4e4f-ad3f-28360c63e44e","uuid":"07136901-0ed5-4ef4-8ffc-8